        "title": "Angry IP Scanner ",
        "content": "## **Angry IP Scanner - Quick Overview**\n\n### **What is it?**\n- Free, open-source network scanner for Windows, Mac, and Linux\n- Scans IP addresses and ports to discover devices on a network\n- Lightweight, fast, and doesn't require installation (portable version available)\n\n---\n\n## **Key Uses & Purposes**\n\n### **üîç Network Discovery**\n- Find all devices connected to your network\n- Identify unknown/unauthorized devices\n- Map your local network structure\n\n### **üñ•Ô∏è Device Information Gathering**\n- Shows device hostnames (if available)\n- Detects MAC addresses and manufacturers\n- Identifies open ports on discovered devices\n\n### **üö® Security Auditing**\n- Find open ports that could be security risks\n- Detect potentially vulnerable services\n- Identify misconfigured network devices\n\n### **üåê Network Troubleshooting**\n- Check which devices are online/offline\n- Verify IP address conflicts\n- Test network connectivity issues\n\n---\n\n## **How It Works (Simple Explanation)**\n1. **You specify an IP range** (e.g., 192.168.1.1 to 192.168.1.255)\n2. **Tool pings each address** to check if device is alive\n3. **Scans ports** (optional) to see what services are running\n4. **Displays results** in easy-to-read table format\n5. **Can export data** to CSV, XML, or text files\n\n---\n\n## **Who Uses It?**\n- **IT Administrators** - Network monitoring and management\n- **Security Professionals** - Basic penetration testing and audits\n- **Home Users** - Checking their home network security\n- **Developers** - Testing network applications\n- **Students** - Learning about networking concepts\n\n "
