        "title": "üïµÔ∏è Wireshark Cheat Sheet",
        "content": "Here's a **clean, practical, and easy-to-use Wireshark Cheat Sheet**‚Äîorganized by real-world tasks, with live examples and quick-reference syntax for network analysis and security investigations.\n\n---\n\n# üïµÔ∏è **Wireshark Cheat Sheet**  \n*Capture, analyze, and troubleshoot network traffic like a pro.*\n\n---\n\n## üß∞ **1. Getting Started**\n\n| Action | How To |\n|-------|--------|\n| **Start Capture** | Click on a network interface (e.g., `eth0`, `Wi-Fi`) in the main window. |\n| **Stop Capture** | Click the red ‚ñ† (Stop) button. |\n| **Save Capture** | `File ‚Üí Save As` ‚Üí `.pcapng` (recommended) or `.pcap`. |\n| **Open Capture** | `File ‚Üí Open` or drag `.pcap` file into Wireshark. |\n\n> ‚úÖ **Pro Tip**: Run Wireshark as **non-root** using `dumpcap` permissions (set during install on Linux).\n\n---\n\n## üîç **2. Display Filters (Applied *After* Capture)**  \n*Type in the filter bar at the top.*\n\n### üîπ **Basic Filters**\n| Filter | Purpose |\n|-------|--------|\n| `ip.addr == 192.168.1.10` | All traffic to/from this IP |\n| `ip.src == 10.0.0.5` | Only packets **from** this IP |\n| `ip.dst == 8.8.8.8` | Only packets **to** this IP |\n| `tcp.port == 443` | HTTPS traffic (TCP) |\n| `udp.port == 53` | DNS traffic (UDP) |\n| `http` | All HTTP traffic |\n| `dns` | DNS queries/responses |\n| `icmp` | Ping (ICMP) packets |\n| `arp` | Address Resolution Protocol traffic |\n| `tls` or `ssl` | Encrypted TLS/SSL sessions |\n\n### üîπ **Advanced Filters**\n| Filter | Purpose |\n|-------|--------|\n| `http.request.method == \"POST\"` | HTTP POST requests |\n| `http.response.code == 200` | Successful HTTP responses |\n| `http contains \"password\"` | Search for ‚Äúpassword‚Äù in HTTP payloads |\n| `tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 0` | New TCP connections (SYN only) |\n| `tcp.stream eq 12` | View all packets in TCP stream #12 |\n| `frame.len > 1500` | Packets larger than standard MTU (possible fragmentation or tunneling) |\n| `ip.ttl < 10` | Suspiciously low TTL (possible tunneling or spoofing) |\n\n### üîπ **Filter Operators**\n| Operator | Meaning |\n|--------|--------|\n| `==` | Equal |\n| `!=` | Not equal |\n| `>` / `<` | Greater/less than |\n| `>=` / `<=` | Greater/less than or equal |\n| `&&` or `and` | Logical AND |\n| `||` or `or` | Logical OR |\n| `!` or `not` | Negation |\n\n> üí° **Shortcut**: Right-click any field in **Packet Details** ‚Üí **Apply as Filter**.\n\n---\n\n## üéØ **3. Capture Filters (BPF Syntax ‚Äì Applied *Before* Capture)**  \n*Set via ‚ÄúCapture ‚Üí Options ‚Üí Capture Filter‚Äù*\n\n> ‚ö†Ô∏è Uses **Berkeley Packet Filter (BPF)** syntax ‚Äì **no spaces around `==`**, and **different keywords**.\n\n| Filter | Purpose |\n|-------|--------|\n| `host 192.168.1.1` | Traffic to/from this IP |\n| `net 10.0.0.0/24` | All traffic in subnet |\n| `port 22` | All SSH traffic (TCP or UDP) |\n| `tcp port 80` | Only TCP on port 80 |\n| `udp port 53` | Only DNS (UDP) |\n| `not arp` | Exclude ARP (reduces noise) |\n| `host 192.168.1.10 and port 443` | Traffic to/from host on HTTPS |\n| `ether host aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:ff` | Filter by MAC address |\n\n> ‚ùå **Not allowed**: `http`, `dns` ‚Äî these are **display filters only** (require protocol dissection).\n\n---\n\n## üîó **4. Following Streams (Reconstruct Conversations)**\n\n1. Right-click any **TCP** or **UDP** packet.\n2. Go to **Follow ‚Üí TCP Stream** (or **UDP Stream**).\n3. View full client/server conversation in plain text (e.g., HTTP headers, chat messages, API calls).\n\n> üìå **Use Case**: Extract login credentials, API keys, or malware C2 commands from unencrypted traffic.\n\n---\n\n## üìä **5. Key Analysis Tools (Statistics Menu)**\n\n| Tool | Use Case |\n|------|--------|\n| **Conversations** (`Statistics ‚Üí Conversations`) | See top talkers (IP pairs, volume, duration) |\n| **Endpoints** | List all devices in the capture |\n| **Protocol Hierarchy** | % of traffic by protocol (e.g., 60% TLS, 20% DNS) |\n| **IO Graphs** | Visualize traffic spikes over time (great for DoS detection) |\n| **HTTP ‚Üí Packet Counter** | Count HTTP requests/responses by code |\n| **Expert Info** (`Analyze ‚Üí Expert Info`) | Warnings/errors (e.g., retransmissions, duplicate ACKs) |\n\n---\n\n## üõ°Ô∏è **6. Security & Forensics Tips**\n\n| Task | Technique |\n|------|---------|\n| **Detect Port Scans** | Look for sequential `tcp.port` attempts to one host with `tcp.flags.syn == 1` |\n| **Find Data Exfiltration** | Large outbound `frame.len` to unknown external IPs |\n| **Spot Malware C2** | Repeated DNS requests to strange domains (`dns.qry.name contains \"xyz123\"`) |\n| **Analyze TLS** | Check `tls.handshake.certificate` for suspicious domains |\n| **VLAN Traffic** | Use `vlan.id == 100` to isolate VLAN 100 traffic |\n| **Decrypt HTTPS (if you have key)** | Use SSL/TLS key log file: `Edit ‚Üí Preferences ‚Üí Protocols ‚Üí TLS ‚Üí (key log file)` |\n\n> üîê **Note**: You **cannot decrypt TLS** without the private key or session keys (e.g., from browser `SSLKEYLOGFILE`).\n\n---\n\n## üß™ **Live Example: Find All Failed Login Attempts**\n\n1. Capture traffic on a web server.\n2. Apply display filter:\n   ```text\n   http.response.code == 401\n   ```\n3. Follow TCP stream on matching packets ‚Üí inspect credentials in POST data (if unencrypted).\n\n> ‚úÖ Works only on **HTTP** ‚Äì not HTTPS (unless decrypted).\n\n---\n\n## üíæ **Save & Share**\n\n- **Export specific packets**: `File ‚Üí Export Specified Packets`\n- **Export objects**: `File ‚Üí Export Objects ‚Üí HTTP` (grab images, files from web traffic!)\n- **Colorize packets**: Right-click packet ‚Üí `Colorize Conversation` ‚Üí easier visual tracking.\n\n---\n\n> üåê **Official Resources**:  \n> - Download: [https://www.wireshark.org](https://www.wireshark.org)  \n> - Display Filter Reference: [https://www.wireshark.org/docs/dfref/](https://www.wireshark.org/docs/dfref/)\n\n---\n\nLet me know if you‚Äôd like a **printable PDF version**, a **quick-reference one-pager**, or examples for **specific protocols** (e.g., DNS tunneling, SMB attacks, etc.)!"
