        "title": "Wireshark Example: Detecting ARP Spoofing",
        "content": "Absolutely! Here's **another live, hands-on Wireshark example**‚Äîthis time focused on **detecting and analyzing an ARP spoofing (MITM) attack** on a local network.\n\n> üîç **Scenario**: Users on your internal network (`192.168.1.0/24`) are reporting intermittent connectivity and being redirected to fake login pages. You suspect an **ARP spoofing attack** (a common step in Man-in-the-Middle attacks).\n\n---\n\n## üß™ **Live Wireshark Example: Detecting ARP Spoofing**\n\n### ‚úÖ Step 1: Start Capture on the LAN Interface\n1. Open **Wireshark**.\n2. Select your **wired or Wi-Fi interface** (the one connected to the local network).\n3. Start capture **without a filter** (ARP is local and fast‚Äîyou need full visibility).\n\n> ‚ö†Ô∏è **Tip**: Run this on a machine in the same subnet as the suspected attack.\n\n---\n\n### ‚úÖ Step 2: Apply an ARP Display Filter\nIn the filter bar, type:\n```text\narp\n```\nNow you only see **ARP packets**‚Äîused to map IP addresses to MAC addresses.\n\n---\n\n### ‚úÖ Step 3: Look for Duplicate MACs (Key Sign of Spoofing)\nIn the **Packet List**, watch for:\n- **Multiple IPs claiming the same MAC address**\n- **One MAC responding for many IPs**\n\nüîç **Normal behavior**:\n- `192.168.1.1` ‚Üí `aa:bb:cc:00:00:01` (router)\n- `192.168.1.10` ‚Üí `dd:ee:ff:00:00:10` (user PC)\n\nüîç **Malicious behavior**:\n- `192.168.1.1` ‚Üí `11:22:33:aa:bb:cc` ‚Üê **attacker MAC**\n- `192.168.1.10` ‚Üí `11:22:33:aa:bb:cc` ‚Üê **same attacker MAC!**\n\n‚Üí This means the attacker is **impersonating both the router and the victim**.\n\n---\n\n### ‚úÖ Step 4: Use Statistics to Confirm\nGo to:\n**Statistics ‚Üí Endpoints ‚Üí Ethernet**\n\nLook at the **MAC address column**:\n- Is one MAC (e.g., `11:22:33:aa:bb:cc`) associated with **multiple IP addresses**?\n- Does it appear far more than others?\n\n‚úÖ **That‚Äôs your attacker.**\n\n---\n\n### ‚úÖ Step 5: Identify the Attacker‚Äôs Machine\nNote the suspicious MAC (e.g., `11:22:33:aa:bb:cc`). Now:\n1. Filter by it:\n   ```text\n   eth.addr == 11:22:33:aa:bb:cc\n   ```\n2. Look at **all traffic** from that MAC.\n3. Check if it‚Äôs:\n   - Forwarding traffic (MITM),\n   - Running `dsniff`, `ettercap`, or `arpspoof`,\n   - Making unexpected DNS or HTTP requests.\n\nYou can also check your **DHCP server logs** or **switch CAM table** to find the physical port.\n\n---\n\n### ‚úÖ Step 6: (Optional) Detect in Real Time with Alerts\nWhile capturing, go to:\n**Analyze ‚Üí Expert Info ‚Üí Notes/Warnings**\n\nLook for:\n- ‚ÄúDuplicate use of [IP] detected (MAC1 vs MAC2)‚Äù\n- ‚ÄúARP ACK without preceding request‚Äù\n\nWireshark will **flag inconsistencies automatically**.\n\n---\n\n### üõ°Ô∏è Prevention Tip\n- Enable **DHCP Snooping + Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI)** on enterprise switches.\n- Use **static ARP entries** for critical devices (not scalable, but effective).\n- Deploy **ARP monitoring tools** like `arpwatch`.\n\n---\n\n## üìù Summary: ARP Spoofing Indicators in Wireshark\n\n| Indicator | What to Look For |\n|--------|------------------|\n| **Duplicate MAC** | Same MAC mapped to multiple IPs |\n| **Excessive ARP** | One host sending ARP replies for many IPs |\n| **Gratuitous ARP** | Unsolicited ARP announcements (common in attacks) |\n| **Expert Warnings** | ‚ÄúDuplicate IP use‚Äù messages |\n\n---\n\n> ‚úÖ **Real-World Impact**: This technique was used in attacks like **Ettercap MITM**, **Evil Twin**, and credential harvesting via fake HTTPS portals.\n\n---\n\nWant a **third live example**? Try one of these:\n- üì• **Analyzing a phishing email: tracking a malicious download**\n- üîê **Decrypting TLS traffic using a browser‚Äôs SSLKEYLOGFILE**\n- üö® **Detecting DNS tunneling exfiltration**\n\nJust say the word!"
